{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PskYwThR1daDsr6NQvGMFN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# TimeAlign\n2\t\n3\t**A history timeline placement game.** You're shown a historical event — title, image,\n4\tand a one-line summary, **with the date hidden** — and you slot it onto a shared timeline:\n5\t**before, after, or between** the events already placed. Commit to reveal the real date,\n6\tscore the guess, and dive deeper on Wikipedia. In the spirit of the board game *Timeline*\n7\tand NYT's *Timelines*.\n8\t\n9\t▶ **Live:** https://timealign-initial-plat.open-platform.sh\n10\t\n11\t## How to play\n12\t\n13\t1. **Pick a puzzle** from the landing page — each shows its theme, difficulty, event count,\n14\t   and the year range it covers.\n15\t2. The board opens with **one anchor event already placed, its date shown**, as a reference\n16\t   point. The timeline runs top-to-bottom and is labelled **\"Earlier in time ↑\"** at the top\n17\t   and **\"Later in time ↓\"** at the bottom, so which end is which is never in doubt.\n18\t3. You're handed the remaining events **one at a time**, date hidden. The spots you can place\n19\t   into are **marked gaps** — dashed slots with a \"＋ Place here\" cue between every card\n20\t   (including before-first and after-last). Read the card, **tap a gap**, then tap **Commit**.\n21\t   Tap-to-place — no dragging, works on phone and desktop.\n22\t4. **On commit the real date is revealed.** Correct → the card locks in showing its date,\n23\t   **+100 points** plus a **+25 streak bonus** per consecutive correct. Wrong → the card snaps\n24\t   to where it actually belongs, **0 points, streak resets**. Either way the timeline stays\n25\t   chronologically valid, so the next placement is always against the truth.\n26\t5. When every event is placed, the **results screen** shows your accuracy (e.g. `5 / 6`),\n27\t   final score, and a **\"dive deeper\" Wikipedia link** for every event. Replay or pick another.\n28\t\n29\t## What's in the box\n30\t\n31\tFour hand-authored demo puzzles, easy → hard:\n32\t\n33\t- **Turning Points in World History** — 1776 → 2007\n34\t- **The Space Race** — 1957 → 2018\n35\t- **Landmark Music Releases** — 1956 → 2014\n36\t- **Birth of the Internet Age** — 1969 → 2009\n37\t\n38\tEvent thumbnails are a progressive enhancement: the client lazy-loads each one from the\n39\tWikipedia REST summary endpoint and falls back to a clean typographic tile if it's offline,\n40\tso the game never depends on the network.\n41\t\n42\t## Design foundation\n43\t\n44\tThe UI is **content-first**, modelled closely on Wikipedia's stark, typography-led\n45\tpresentation — a shared system future features build on. It lives in `src/ui.ts` and every\n46\tpage composes from it:\n47\t\n48\t- **Two typefaces only:** Linux Libertine for section titles, Helvetica for everything else.\n49\t- **All text is black; the only colour is the blue of hyperlinks.** No custom palette, no\n50\t  decorative borders, no all-caps labels — just thin Wikipedia-style rules, tables, and\n51\t  infoboxes. (The game board keeps a single functional green/red for transient correct/wrong\n52\t  placement feedback — that is state, not decoration.)\n53\t- **Header structure** mirrors a Wikipedia article: the **page header** is just the page\n54\t  title (_Timelines Demo_) and, on sub-pages, a back arrow — nothing else. Below it sits a\n55\t  **body header** at content width — two thin horizontal rules with utility info between them\n56\t  (left-aligned context, right-aligned links + the auth chip), present on every page.\n57\t- **Reusable structures:** boxed **infoboxes** (the catalogue summary on the home page) and\n58\t  dense **`wikitable`** data tables — no marketing hero, no floating pills, no excessive\n59\t  whitespace.\n60\t\n61\tThe **home page** reads as a short article: a lead paragraph, a catalogue infobox, a brief\n62\t\"How to play\" block, and the puzzle picker as a scannable table (theme · difficulty ·\n63\tevents · years). The **game board** carries the puzzle metadata as a plain caption and runs\n64\ta clean vertical timeline inside its own rectangular container, so its width stays constant\n65\tas it grows; the game engine logic is unchanged.\n66\t\n67\t## Architecture\n68\t\n69\t- **Server-rendered HTML + inline vanilla JS** — no React, no bundler. The landing page\n70\t  (`src/homepage.ts`) and the game board (`src/game.ts`) are template strings; the board's\n71\t  game engine ships verbatim as a single inline script. The shared design system (tokens,\n72\t  page header, Wikipedia-style body header, infobox/table styles, auth chip) lives in\n73\t  `src/ui.ts`.\n74\t- **Typed puzzle API.** The catalogue (`src/puzzles.ts`) is the single source of truth: a\n75\t  TypeBox `Puzzle` schema types the API responses (→ honest auto-generated OpenAPI at\n76\t  `/openapi.json`) **and** every catalogue entry is validated against it at module load, so a\n77\t  malformed puzzle fails fast instead of shipping. The same schema is the contract a future\n78\t  auto-sourcing pipeline (Wikidata/Wikipedia) must emit.\n79\t- **No database in v1** — the game is stateless and scoring is local to the browser session.\n80\t  (Postgres is provisioned and powers optional Forgejo SSO, which stays out of the way.)\n81\t\n82\t### Endpoints\n83\t\n84\t| Route                | What                                                  |\n85\t| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n86\t| `GET /`              | Landing page + puzzle picker                          |\n87\t| `GET /play/:id`      | The game board (full puzzle inlined; engine hides dates) |\n88\t| `GET /api/puzzles`   | Puzzle summaries — date-free (never leak a date pre-placement) |\n89\t| `GET /api/puzzles/:id` | One full puzzle, validated against the `Puzzle` schema |\n90\t| `GET /openapi.json`  | Auto-generated OpenAPI 3.1 (Swagger UI at `/openapi`) |\n91\t| `GET /version`, `/readyz`, `/api/me` | Meta / health / current user            |\n92\t\n93\t## Running locally\n94\t\n95\t```bash\n96\tnpm ci\n97\tnpm run lint        # biome\n98\tnpm run typecheck   # tsc --noEmit\n99\tnpm run build       # tsc → dist/\n100\tnpm start           # node dist/server.js  (listens on :8080)\n101\t```\n102\t\n103\tAuth needs the platform-provided OAuth env to be set, but the game itself does **not** —\n104\topen `http://localhost:8080` and play.\n105\t\n106\t## Not in v1 (deliberately)\n107\t\n108\t- **Live Wikidata/Wikipedia puzzle sourcing.** The goal is puzzles on demand for any era or\n109\t  topic; v1 ships the hand-authored demo set with an honest \"more, auto-sourced, coming\" note.\n110\t  The typed `Puzzle` schema is already the contract that pipeline will emit.\n111\t- **Accounts-gating / leaderboards.** Auth is optional and out of the way; scoring is per-session.\n112\t- **Event spans / eras.** Every event is a discrete, single-instant moment.\n113\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ea97c4a2-67f7-4ff7-8c74-f9bccb4cced2","uuid":"b26678fa-9d57-4b91-88e7-0de2b16e4848","timestamp":"2026-06-17T12:35:37.441Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/data/work/worker-plat-timealign-initial-mqi1ilmpq/README.md","content":"# TimeAlign\n\n**A history timeline placement game.** You're shown a historical event — title, image,\nand a one-line summary, **with the date hidden** — and you slot it onto a shared timeline:\n**before, after, or between** the events already placed. Commit to reveal the real date,\nscore the guess, and dive deeper on Wikipedia. In the spirit of the board game *Timeline*\nand NYT's *Timelines*.\n\n▶ **Live:** https://timealign-initial-plat.open-platform.sh\n\n## How to play\n\n1. **Pick a puzzle** from the landing page — each shows its theme, difficulty, event count,\n   and the year range it covers.\n2. The board opens with **one anchor event already placed, its date shown**, as a reference\n   point. The timeline runs top-to-bottom and is labelled **\"Earlier in time ↑\"** at the top\n   and **\"Later in time ↓\"** at the bottom, so which end is which is never in doubt.\n3. You're handed the remaining events **one at a time**, date hidden. The spots you can place\n   into are **marked gaps** — dashed slots with a \"＋ Place here\" cue between every card\n   (including before-first and after-last). Read the card, **tap a gap**, then tap **Commit**.\n   Tap-to-place — no dragging, works on phone and desktop.\n4. **On commit the real date is revealed.** Correct → the card locks in showing its date,\n   **+100 points** plus a **+25 streak bonus** per consecutive correct. Wrong → the card snaps\n   to where it actually belongs, **0 points, streak resets**. Either way the timeline stays\n   chronologically valid, so the next placement is always against the truth.\n5. When every event is placed, the **results screen** shows your accuracy (e.g. `5 / 6`),\n   final score, and a **\"dive deeper\" Wikipedia link** for every event. Replay or pick another.\n\n## What's in the box\n\nFour hand-authored demo puzzles, easy → hard:\n\n- **Turning Points in World History** — 1776 → 2007\n- **The Space Race** — 1957 → 2018\n- **Landmark Music Releases** — 1956 → 2014\n- **Birth of the Internet Age** — 1969 → 2009\n\nEvent thumbnails are a progressive enhancement: the client lazy-loads each one from the\nWikipedia REST summary endpoint and falls back to a clean typographic tile if it's offline,\nso the game never depends on the network.\n\n## Design foundation\n\nThe UI is **content-first**, modelled closely on Wikipedia's stark, typography-led\npresentation — a shared system future features build on. It lives in `src/ui.ts` and every\npage composes from it:\n\n- **Two typefaces only:** Linux Libertine for section titles, Helvetica for everything else.\n- **All text is black; the only colour is the blue of hyperlinks.** No custom palette, no\n  decorative borders, no all-caps labels — just thin Wikipedia-style rules, tables, and\n  infoboxes. (The game board keeps a single functional green/red for transient correct/wrong\n  placement feedback — that is state, not decoration.)\n- **Header structure** mirrors a Wikipedia article: the **page header** is just the page\n  title (_Timelines Demo_) and, on sub-pages, a back arrow — nothing else. Below it sits a\n  **body header** at content width — two thin horizontal rules with utility info between them\n  (left-aligned context, right-aligned links + the auth chip), present on every page.\n- **Reusable structures:** boxed **infoboxes** (the catalogue summary on the home page) and\n  dense **`wikitable`** data tables — no marketing hero, no floating pills, no excessive\n  whitespace.\n\nThe **home page** reads as a short article: a lead paragraph, a catalogue infobox, a brief\n\"How to play\" block, and the puzzle picker as a scannable table (theme · difficulty ·\nevents · years). The **game board** carries the puzzle metadata as a plain caption and runs\na clean vertical timeline inside its own rectangular container, so its width stays constant\nas it grows; the game engine logic is unchanged.\n\n## Architecture\n\n- **Server-rendered HTML + inline vanilla JS** — no React, no bundler. The landing page\n  (`src/homepage.ts`) and the game board (`src/game.ts`) are template strings; the board's\n  game engine ships verbatim as a single inline script. The shared design system (tokens,\n  page header, Wikipedia-style body header, infobox/table styles, auth chip) lives in\n  `src/ui.ts`.\n- **Typed puzzle API.** The catalogue (`src/puzzles.ts`) is the single source of truth: a\n  TypeBox `Puzzle` schema types the API responses (→ honest auto-generated OpenAPI at\n  `/openapi.json`) **and** every catalogue entry is validated against it at module load, so a\n  malformed puzzle fails fast instead of shipping. The same schema is the contract a future\n  auto-sourcing pipeline (Wikidata/Wikipedia) must emit.\n- **No database in v1** — the game is stateless and scoring is local to the browser session.\n  (Postgres is provisioned and powers optional Forgejo SSO, which stays out of the way.)\n\n### Endpoints\n\n| Route                | What                                                  |\n| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n| `GET /`              | Landing page + puzzle picker                          |\n| `GET /play/:id`      | The game board (full puzzle inlined; engine hides dates) |\n| `GET /api/puzzles`   | Puzzle summaries — date-free (never leak a date pre-placement) |\n| `GET /api/puzzles/:id` | One full puzzle, validated against the `Puzzle` schema |\n| `GET /openapi.json`  | Auto-generated OpenAPI 3.1 (Swagger UI at `/openapi`) |\n| `GET /version`, `/readyz`, `/api/me` | Meta / health / current user            |\n\n## Running locally\n\n```bash\nnpm ci\nnpm run lint        # biome\nnpm run typecheck   # tsc --noEmit\nnpm run build       # tsc → dist/\nnpm start           # node dist/server.js  (listens on :8080)\n```\n\nAuth needs the platform-provided OAuth env to be set, but the game itself does **not** —\nopen `http://localhost:8080` and play.\n\n## Not in v1 (deliberately)\n\n- **Live Wikidata/Wikipedia puzzle sourcing.** The goal is puzzles on demand for any era or\n  topic; v1 ships the hand-authored demo set with an honest \"more, auto-sourced, coming\" note.\n  The typed `Puzzle` schema is already the contract that pipeline will emit.\n- **Accounts-gating / leaderboards.** Auth is optional and out of the way; scoring is per-session.\n- **Event spans / eras.** Every event is a discrete, single-instant moment.\n","numLines":113,"startLine":1,"totalLines":113}}}
